{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/calculate-your-monthly-recurring-customer-by-cohort-analysis-3d39473482b7", "time": 1683015388.3359559, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/calculate-your-monthly-recurring-customer-by-cohort-analysis-3d39473482b7/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Calculate your monthly recurring customer by Cohort Analysis | by Md. Hasibul Islam | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Calculate your monthly recurring customer by Cohort Analysis", "description": "Imagine you have opened a business, your business is going well. But this could be better. Some of your customers may ask you, \u201cHey man, I often buy from you, don\u2019t I deserve some offer?\u201d. Now you\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.kaggle.com/mrmining/online-retail?", "anchor_text": "online retail", "paragraph_index": 1}], "all_paragraphs": ["Imagine you have opened a business, your business is going well. But this could be better. Some of your customers may ask you, \u201cHey man, I often buy from you, don\u2019t I deserve some offer?\u201d. Now you think that \u201cWell, I should see who are my recurring customers! I should offer them more so that they keep coming regularly.\u201d. And you can do it by cohort analysis. Today I\u2019ll discuss cohort analysis using python. Let\u2019s dive into the ocean of data analysis.", "For this analysis, I have used the online retail data set from Kaggle. Go to the link and download it. Okay, so let\u2019s see what\u2019s inside our dataset!", "First of all, import the necessary libraries.", "Now load the dataset and observe what\u2019s inside it.", "So here\u2019re the first five rows of our dataset that has columns,", "InvoiceNo: Simply Invoice number of the purchase.", "UnitPrice: Price of each single product", "CustomerID: A unique string by which each customer will be identified", "Okay, let\u2019s dive in more. Now we shall make a function to get the month number of each invoice number so that we can know on which month the product got purchased.", "Look at the last column where I marked the middle part, which is \u2018month\u2019. We shall use it later. Now let\u2019s see which customers visited on which months. For that, we shall use pandas \u2018groupby\u2019. Don\u2019t worry. it\u2019s easy.", "Now let\u2019s see on which month each individual customer made their first purchase.", "Now this \u2018CohortMonth\u2019 is the time when the customers made their first purchase. Now we shall again make a function to extract on which months the customers came by so that we can get our recurring customers.", "So the marked \u2018CohortIndex\u2019 is the column where we get the difference between the first purchase and all the purchases that the customer made later. So here the first one is \u20181.0\u2019 which means he did that purchase in the same month he did his first purchase.", "Now let\u2019s \u2018groupby\u2019 the customers by \u2018CohortMonth\u2019 and \u2018CohortIndex\u2019 so that we can identify the customers who came to purchase in the same month with the same interval.", "Now we shall take only the first month of each customer to calculate a pivot table so that we can calculate later the recurring customers.", "So we can see only 91 unique customers made 541909 purchases during this period. Let\u2019s make the pivot table.", "Now we can see some NaN values here means From 2010\u201312\u201301 to 2011\u201312\u201301 is in total 13 months. So the first index value has the recurring customers of each 13 months, but the next index 2011\u201301\u201301 has only 12 months difference from 2011\u201312\u201301. That\u2019s why the last row value is NaN. So in the first month, 948 customers came to purchase from which 362 customers returned to buy again in the next month and, it goes on.", "Now we shall take the number of customers that came in each month. Because we want to keep them as a base and the later came by customers will be followers.", "Now we will reshape the data in the interval of 1\u20130 so that we can show a percentage of recurring customers.", "So we have converted the retention rate in percentage. Now let\u2019s plot this in a heatmap to observe our monthly recurring customer percentage.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "I\u2019m a data science enthusiast. Always try to cope up with the upgraded technologies. Connect Me through polok.hasibul@gmail.com."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F3d39473482b7&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fcalculate-your-monthly-recurring-customer-by-cohort-analysis-3d39473482b7&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fcalculate-your-monthly-recurring-customer-by-cohort-analysis-3d39473482b7&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fcalculate-your-monthly-recurring-customer-by-cohort-analysis-3d39473482b7&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav